    <section id="warnings">
      <h2>Warnings</h2>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Romanticizing Failure Is as Dangerous as Fearing It">
        Silicon Valley's "fail fast" culture has produced a counterproductive romanticization of failure that treats it as intrinsically valuable rather than as a potential source of learning. Failure is only valuable when it is studied, learned from, and integrated into better judgment. Celebrating failure without extracting its lessons is not growth — it is expensive entertainment. The goal is not to fail more; it is to learn better.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Some Failures Require Grief Before Analysis">
        Not all failures can be immediately converted into learning exercises. Major losses — a collapsed business that represented years of effort, a relationship that ended badly, a professional humiliation — often require genuine grief before productive analysis is possible. Rushing to "extract the lesson" as an avoidance of grief can actually prevent the deep processing that produces real growth. Allow the emotional reality of loss its space; the analysis will be more honest and more useful when it comes from a place of genuine acceptance rather than defensive premature closure.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Repeating the Same Failure Is Not Learning">
        There is a version of "I learn from failure" that is actually "I repeat the same failure while telling myself I am growing." If you find yourself experiencing the same type of failure repeatedly — the same relationship patterns, the same execution breakdowns, the same strategic blind spots — this is a signal that your post-failure analysis is not reaching the root cause. Deeper examination, possibly with the help of a trusted outsider or therapist, is needed to break the cycle.
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

